Introduction

In this notebook I will be going through some of my used models, both from my personal exercises as models explored in my group project to try and get a better understanding of applying Explaiable AI within different kinds of models

To start of, I will be taking a look at GRAD Cam, I will use this to visually show a heatmap of the most important input pixels for my CNN model used in TrafficSigns and the BOI image recognition, as well as trying it on a fully pre-trained model with high accuracy, as this will help show the possible differences and observations that can be made from using this tool on less accurate models.

Traffic Signs CNN

Below, I will try using the CNN trained with transferlearning on roadsigns, to create a Gradcam visualization of the POI taken by the model.
Because, I did not save this model, I will have to retrain it first.

Create a key-value map to re-index the datasets, as tensorflow for some reason messes up the index count, by ordering alphabetically even if the classes are numeric...

In[]:
train_val_index_table = tf.lookup.StaticHashTable(
    initializer=tf.lookup.KeyValueTensorInitializer(
        keys=tf.constant(np.arange(len(original_class_names)), dtype=tf.int32),
        values=tf.constant(list(map(int, original_class_names)), dtype=tf.int32),
    ),
    default_value= tf.constant(len(original_class_names), dtype=tf.int32)
)

def re_index_labels(image, label):
    # Use the hash table to map old labels to new labels
    new_label = train_val_index_table.lookup(label)
    return image, new_label

train_dataset = train_dataset.map(re_index_labels)
val_dataset = val_dataset.map(re_index_labels)
test_dataset = test_dataset.map(re_index_labels)

Create the model.
NOTE: This model actually has an additional Conv2D layer, as I will need to reference the last convolutional layer during Grad CAM heatmap generation, and if the last conv layer is inside the referenced pre-trained model, I will have to flatten those pre-trained layers into the parent model, which causes many issues with the connections between layers, to the point it is not worth the effort (While, I did spend a significant time getting that working, I ended up scratching it and do not have any of the code cells left, as they were not brought over from my testing notebook directly in the Traffic Signs ipynb to this notebook, but in short, flattening the layers destroys the Input layer for some reason causing the model to not be able to be built, but specifying a new input layer while building the flattened model, caused errors that I could only find might be caused by some internal model layer indexing issues).

pretrained_model = keras.applications.Xception(
    weights='imagenet',  # Load weights pre-trained on ImageNet
    input_shape=(71, 71, 3), # Input shape of our dataset images
    include_top=False)  # Exclude the classifier layer, as our own will be used

pretrained_model.trainable = False

model = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.Input(shape=(71, 71, 3)),
        keras.layers.Rescaling(scale=1 / 127.5, offset=-1),
        pretrained_model,
        keras.layers.Conv2D(512, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
        keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(),
        keras.layers.Dense(len(original_class_names)),
    ])

Now, lets create the GRAD Cam heatmap, that can be used to visualize the pixel node activation of the model for a given image.
For this I primarily followed this Grad-cam guide, which goes over creating this heatmap for an xception model (which is what the traffic sign model used for transfer learning)

First, lets setup the logic that will go through the model and return a heatmap of the most prominently activated input pixels.
NOTE: I am pretty sure the guide messes up and selects the wrong last convolutional layer, while this layer comes in later as an activation layer, it is not the final convolution layer (looking around on the internet it seems that my approach is more used), from my personal experimenting I found that selecting the final layer with my method actually returns a much more defined heatmap than the more generic activation layer.
I am not sure if this indicates that I am actually selecting a single convolutional layer, and I would be better off selecting the final activation layer (but I was unable to find a programatical way of selecting this layer, as the prediction layer is also of activation type, while summary of the layers shows otherwise)

In[]:
def get_last_conv_layer(model):
    last_conv_layer = None
    for layer in reversed(model.layers):
        if 'conv2d' in layer.name.lower():  # Check if the layer is a convolutional layer
            last_conv_layer = layer
            break  # Stop after finding the last convolutional layer
    return last_conv_layer

def make_gradcam_heatmap(img_array, model, last_conv_layer_name, pred_index=None):
    # Create a new thin model, that exclusively takes the original model's input tensor (the image pixels),  
    # and the model's last convolutional output values alongside it's normal output (the classification)
    grad_model = keras.models.Model(
        model.inputs, [model.get_layer(last_conv_layer_name).output, model.output]
    )

    # Then, we compute the gradient of the top predicted class for our input image
    # with respect to the activations of the last conv layer
    with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
        # Get the model's output of the last conv layer and prediction layer for given image
        last_conv_layer_output, preds = grad_model(img_array)
        if pred_index is None: # Find the predicted classification, by obtaining the highest activation node
            pred_index = tf.argmax(preds[0])
        class_channel = preds[:, pred_index] # Get the predicted class for every image in the batch

    grads = tape.gradient(class_channel, last_conv_layer_output) # Calculate the importance gradient for the final conv output layer in relation to the predicted classes, 
                                                                 # this effectively merges all predictions and their conv layer outputs together to get a general idea of importance

    pooled_grads = tf.reduce_mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2)) # Reduce the multi dimensional gradient output into a single dimension to convert into 2D heatmap

    last_conv_layer_output = last_conv_layer_output[0] # Get the conv2d layer's feature map for the first image in the batch
    heatmap = last_conv_layer_output @ pooled_grads[..., tf.newaxis] # Calculate the dotproduct of the conv2d feature mapping against the gradient importance
    heatmap = tf.squeeze(heatmap) # Convert the heatmap to a 2D array

    heatmap = tf.maximum(heatmap, 0) / tf.math.reduce_max(heatmap) # Normalize the heatmap values between 0-1
    return heatmap.numpy()

You can already see, a very big reason why the model performs very inefficiently, due to the extremely low 71x71 input size, throughout the model's MaxPooling (downsampling), the convolutional layers end up only having a 3x3 feature set to work with, which is most likely not big enough to notice small changes, such as the text on a sign

Lets overlay this heatmap on the image it was predicting

In[]:
import matplotlib
def apply_heatmap(heatmap, image_array, heatmap_opacity=0.4): # Returns image_array with heatmap as overlay
    heatmap = np.uint8(255 * heatmap) # Rescale heatmap to a range 0-255

    jet = matplotlib.colormaps["jet"] # Use jet colormap to colorize heatmap

    # Use RGB values of the colormap
    jet_colors = jet(np.arange(256))[:, :3]
    jet_heatmap = jet_colors[heatmap]

    # Create an image with RGB colorized heatmap
    jet_heatmap = keras.utils.array_to_img(jet_heatmap)
    jet_heatmap = jet_heatmap.resize((image_array.shape[1], image_array.shape[0]))
    jet_heatmap = keras.utils.img_to_array(jet_heatmap)

    # Superimpose the heatmap on original image
    superimposed_img_array = jet_heatmap * heatmap_opacity + image_array
    return keras.utils.array_to_img(superimposed_img_array)

High accuracy CNN

For this, I will be using the pretrained Xception model, just as done in the guide mentioned earlier.

As mentioned before, I am not 100% sure what layer to select as the final convolutional layer, while I do think the top image is much more interesting as it seems like the model is paying attention to the chest of the bird as it has a distinct color and might help identify it against other birds.
This thought process does indicate however, that using my programatic approach to obtaining the final conv layer, actually shows the activation of that feature layer, while the image below shows the geral area of interest for the model which is more in line with generic Grad-cam usage.

That does give me the idea, that I might be able to create a subplot list of all conv layers and see what each layers is paying attention to in the model, so lets try that!

Yep, my assumption seems to have proven correctly, and this shows some really cool visualization of the 4 convolutional layers in the Xception layer, and how they were activated based on the image, with the second layer actually clearly paying attention to the background instead of the bird itself.

This did prove that my get_last_conv_layer was getting the actual feature layer instead of the final activation layer, so I have adjusted the method below.

In[]:
def get_last_conv_activation_layer(model):
    last_conv_layer = None
    for layer in reversed(model.layers):
        if 'conv2' in layer.name.lower():  # Check if the layer is a convolutional layer
            last_conv_layer = layer
            break  # Stop after finding the last convolutional layer
    return last_conv_layer

Now let's do the Grad CAM again, which I should be an expert at at this point

First, lets create a method that can turn the black background of an image into a white one

In[]:
def image_array_black_to_white(img_array):
    # First normalize the image array into a numpy array by translating it into a PIL Image first
    image_array = np.array(keras.utils.array_to_img(img_array))
    # Create a mask for the black pixels and convert them to white
    black_mask = np.all(image_array == (0, 0, 0), axis=-1)
    image_array[black_mask] = (255, 255, 255)
    return image_array

        heatmap = make_gradcam_heatmap(images[i:], boi_model, last_conv_layer.name)

        # Add the heatmap to the original image
        img = apply_heatmap(heatmap, image_array, heatmap_opacity=0.6)
        
        predicted_class = class_names[np.argmax(predictions[i])]
        plt.title(predicted_class)
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.axis("off")

Above I have created a matrix of these GRAD-cams and as expected, for every prediction the conv layer was extremely effective at isolating the image, even between image distortions.

SHAP values

Next I want to take a quick look at my OneClassSVM model from the group project, I will look into this model using the SHAP library, this library should be able to give me SHAP values that represent the contribution the feature had to the prediction. I am not 100% sure how this system works for anomaly detection, as from looking around it seems to not really be used for this usecase, but I think it is cool looking into it anyway.

As always, I forgot to save the model I want to use, so I will have to train it again. The model I will be looking at is not the best model I was able to produce using OneClassSVM, but instead it was a trial model to see what happens when I included features that I knew would be poisoneaus to the model's performance if it focussed on those features.
To my suprise however, it seemed that the model completely ignored the features however which I want to learn more about.

Above, I have calculated the SHAP values for the entire dataset, this also includes the trained data as I want to know if the OneClassSVM is internally aware of useless features and will ignore them.
And from the results it seems that my assumption was correct, with the SHAP value based on the OneClassSVM (SGD kernel) model giving an impact score of 0 to the x_port features, as I expected. It however, also gave a 0 impact score for the network_bytes, which I expected to be closer the the display of the event_duration

While, this proves some of my initial thoughts on how the model was training to learn the outlier boundary, the SGD kernel is actually not the kernel that will be used, due to it's mediocre performance in the SUE use-case, instead sigmoid is used which is a far more computationally intensive training model, so I will be training this model next to evaluate further using XAI

From the plots above, you can get a slightly better idea of where the decision boundary is between the features.
The last plot here is especially, interesting knowing that the model basically only took the _source_event_duration into account, the decision scores is linearly correlated with the _source_event_duration, which makes sense when considering that One-class SVM tries to find this correlation on it's own and if it ends up only taking one feature into account, the relation between the decision score and that feature would be linearly related.
Which I suppose was a very smart way for the model to get a good performance for the given dataset, as it seemed to have found that exploiting the data this way was acceptible (very similar to something a neural network might do which is pretty cool).

Convert the shap_samples_df to also include the labels, for possible future evaluation

In[]:
# Create the labeled dataframe
labelled_shap_samples_df_features = shap_features + ["label"]
labelled_shap_samples_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=labelled_shap_samples_df_features)
for idx, row in shap_samples_df.iterrows():

    # Select only the common features in both DataFrames
    shap_samples_common = shap_samples_df[shap_features]
    mf_common = mf_df[shap_features]

    # Create a boolean mask to filter mf_common for matching records
    mask = (mf_common == shap_samples_common).all(axis=1)

    # Extract the matching records from mf_common
    matching_records = mf_common[mask]

    # Display the matching records with all features
    matching_records_full = mf_df[mask]

    # Display the matching records
    labelled_shap_samples_df = pd.concat([labelled_shap_samples_df, matching_records_full.head(1)], ignore_index=True)
